                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>To the Editor of the <hi rend=\"underline\">Occident</hi>:</p>\n            <p>Rev. Sir., Knowing your liberality, in offering<lb/> the columns of your valuable\n                paper for the benefit<lb/> of the Jewish community in general I take the\n                liberty,<lb/> to send you a series of „Translations from the French<lb/> for\n                publishing in your estimated journal, if it be found<lb/> worthy.</p>\n            <p rend=\"align(right)\">Oriental Traditions.</p>\n            <p>Translated from the French By <persName>Zadik<lb/> S. H.</persName></p>\n            <p>The philosopher and the Rabbi.— “Your God<lb/> calls himself in his book a jealous\n                God, who can<lb/> not suffer other gods on his side<del>s</del>, and he<lb/> always\n                shows his abhorrence towards poly-<lb/>theism. But how does it happen, that he<lb/>\n                menaces more the <hi rend=\"underline\">worshippers</hi> of the false<lb/> gods, and\n                seems to hate them more than<lb/> the <hi rend=\"underline\">false gods</hi>\n                themselves? A Greek philosop<lb/>her once inquired so of a Rabbi.</p>\n            <p>But the Rabbi replied him:</p>\n            <p>„A Ring had a disobedient son, and<lb/> besides other naughty hits of all kinds,<lb/>\n                he was malicious enough, to call his<lb/> dogs with his father's name<del>s</del>\n                and<lb/> title. Now should <add>?</add> punish his<lb/> son or the dogs.</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3tb0zf7p/canvas/p1"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
